            "id": "6b18755603cb4734a29c2",
            "questionText": "In a photoelectric effect experiment, a metal surface is illuminated with light of two different wavelengths. The first wavelength, $!$\\lambda_1 = 300 \\text{ nm}$!$, results in a stopping potential of $!$1.5 \\text{ V}$!$. When the wavelength is changed to $!$\\lambda_2 = 200 \\text{ nm}$!$, the stopping potential increases to $!$3.0 \\text{ V}$!$. Determine the work function $!$\\phi$!$ of the metal in electron volts ($!$\\text{eV}$!$). Use $!$h = 6.626 \\times 10^{-34} \\text{ Js}$!$ and $!$c = 3 \\times 10^8 \\text{ m/s}$!$.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "c8e4161d154e40728e1d6",
                    "stepText": "Let's begin by identifying the correct photoelectric effect equation that connects the stopping potential, the photon energy from the light, and the work function. Which one of the following represents this relationship?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "0a84b816-12f2-48c5-b801-70ddcbfa3381"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$eV_s = \\frac{hc}{\\lambda} - \\phi$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$eV_s = \\frac{hc}{\\lambda} + \\phi$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$eV_s = \\phi - \\frac{hc}{\\lambda}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "edb06ec9d828425f9d7d3",
                    "stepText": "Great! Now, using the given values $!$h = 6.626 \\times 10^{-34} \\text{ Js}$!$ and $!$c = 3 \\times 10^8 \\text{ m/s}$!$, multiply them to compute the product $!$hc$!$. Provide your answer in units of $!$\\text{J}\\cdot\\text{m}$!$.",
